label chapter14:

    # [Scene: Courtroom | Morning]

    scene bg ch14_9d8ae5_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, low strings — a steady, downward pull]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Murmur of voices, the soft scrape of chairs, a distant gull cry carried faintly through an open window]
    "The room smells of lemon disinfectant and stale coffee. It's the kind of clean that has erased the marsh from memory — salt and bog mud replaced by paper and polished wood. You notice the absence"
    "like a bruise; the sterile air makes your chest feel hollow, as if the coast itself has been cordoned off."
    "You hold the regulator's receipt — a small square of proof in your palm — and it feels both like an anchor and an accusation. Tonight's filing is a hinge; this morning the hinge squeaks."

    "Judge" "Counsel, proceed."

    "Atlantech Counsel" "Your Honor, the proposed injunction would halt a project that protects hundreds of thousands of dollars in regional infrastructure. The record shows that delaying construction increases risk, threats to jobs, and downward economic cascades. We urge the court to consider the broader public interest."
    "The counsel's voice is a polished blade. It slices into the room with numbers and hypothetical tables; the words are sterile, they don't ask permission to land on the backs of people whose roofs are thin"
    "and whose boats are patched. You watch the volunteers shift, watching numbers become the reasoning for razing the marsh."
    show elena_cruz at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elena_cruz "We are not arguing against safety. We are arguing that safety is not a single, concrete edge. There are many ways to protect people."
    "Her voice is low, steady. You see the weight of municipal responsibility on her shoulders — the same lines around her mouth that have appeared after every storm, after every negotiation. She looks at the judge like someone who has learned to wear hope like armor."
    hide elena_cruz

    scene bg ch14_9d8ae5_2 at full_bg
    "Narration: You can feel the town split like a tide through rock. Some of them think the wall is a reopening of safety; others see it as a permanent eclipse."

    scene bg ch14_9d8ae5_3 at full_bg
    show maren_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maren_voss "The protestors are playing politics with people's livelihoods. Delays translate into price increases, into lost contracts, and—most importantly—into unnecessary exposure. We will not gamble with lives."
    "Maren's smile is all business. The reporters throw questions like bait; she answers with a script and a mirror. On the monitor, the volunteers in the crowd outside appear as a blurry force; she frames them as reckless, not caring for the real costs."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A murmured gasp from the gallery]

    "Volunteer" "They're on the offensive, Amaya."
    "You nod without turning. Your throat is dry. The choice in your pocket — the leaked file some anonymous channel offered last night — feels heavier now. It could stop this. It could make the supposedly objective assessments look like manipulated mosaics. It could make Maren's smile fracture."
    show lucas_herrera at right:
        zoom 0.7

    lucas_herrera "You don't have to do anything rash."
    "He draws close, practical and careful as always. You can feel the faint warmth of him, like a small, steady lamp in the cold room. His gaze flicks to the monitor, to the judge, back to you."
    show amaya_saito at center:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "It's not rash if it's truthful."

    lucas_herrera "Truth is a legal instrument here, not just an idea. If you release that without chain of custody and counsel's backing, Atlantech will shred it, and the court will punish us. They will call it evidence tampering. They will—' (he stops, choosing words) '—they will paint us as reckless leaders."

    amaya_saito "And if we wait, the crews keep hauling concrete. They break the marsh in a week. Some of those houses out there will be cut off by construction or evicted."

    lucas_herrera "I know what would happen out there, Amaya. But I also know what happens in here.' (He nods toward the judge) 'They will throw out anything that appears unvetted and make us pay."
    "You want to speak, to point to the scale of the deception you suspect. You want to rip open the court and let the light get in — but you also know how easily light can burn when it's not handled."

    menu:
        "Meet Lucas's eyes and take a breath":
            "You find steadiness in his look. The world compresses into his inhale. For a second you fold the leak into silence and listen to the legal machinery turn, counting the cost of an immediate blow."
        "Slide your hand toward Dr. Kaito's, as if asking permission":
            "Dr. Kaito's fingers close around yours, rough and warm. He does not speak; he gives you the weight of his patience, and with it, a reminder of slow truths that outlast headlines."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"
    hide maren_voss
    show dr_kaito_mori at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kaito_mori "Law can protect. It can also chain people. If you choose to strike, you must be ready for what binds you afterward."
    "His voice is the anchor your father used to be—slow, low, the kind that names long arcs. You feel his gaze on you like an old tide line."
    "Atlantech Counsel rises again, laying out 'market impacts' with charts. He talks about pension funds, insurance premiums, supply chains. The language is an ocean made of ledger lines; it barely acknowledges the living networks of root and bird and shoreline."

    "Atlantech Counsel" "The court must consider the ripple effects. A halt invites investor flight. The region's economy will contract. Homes are not saved by sentiment."

    "Judge" "Ms. Saito, you will have a chance to present any evidence through proper channels."
    "The words are procedural, small and final. The judge's gavel could be a lighthouse lamp sweeping over a shoreline and missing the marsh hidden in fog."

    "You feel a hand on the back of your chair — Mika's, knuckles white. She mouths something" "People are scared."
    hide lucas_herrera
    show mika_tan at right:
        zoom 0.7

    mika_tan "Some of the dockworkers are being told their hours will be cut if they protest. I heard that at the market — they said contracts depend on the site staying open."
    "A ripple through the crowd. Someone begins to whisper about eviction notices, about contractors arriving and asking questions about who lives where."
    "Your mind does an inventory: the legal receipt in your pocket, Dr. Kaito's counsel, Lucas's steady pragmatism, the hungry press outside. Every option bleeds a sacrifice you are not sure you can bear."

    menu:
        "Step up to the clerk’s table and ask quietly about emergency filings":
            "The clerk is polite but wary. 'There are channels,' she says. 'If you submit it now without counsel, you'll be opening a procedural can.' Her caution buzzes in your ear like a warning bell."
        "Lean over to Lucas and whisper to him to stall for time":
            "Lucas nods minutely; his fingers press into your palm. He will try to slow the process—obtain a formal review, get chain of custody—buy you just enough hours to craft a better strike."

    # --- merge ---
    "Continue"

    "You picture the leak itself: a document with lines redacted and two words scrawled in the margin — deliberate manipulation. You imagine the headline permutations" "Town Sabotages Itself' versus 'Company Lies Exposed."
    "Across the room, the monitor cuts to Maren again. She is now inside the lobby, signing a glossy brochure with a reporter leaning in."
    hide amaya_saito
    show maren_voss at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maren_voss "We respect legitimate scrutiny. But we will not be held hostage by theatrics. Our priority is to protect lives. We are ready to work with responsible stakeholders."
    "There is steel beneath her civility. You can feel, in the way the counsel speaks and in the feed's careful angle, the machinery aligning to defend itself. They have lawyers, PR teams, and deep pockets. You have a town and a receipt."
    hide dr_kaito_mori
    show lucas_herrera at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lucas_herrera "If you release that now, they'll use it to charge you. They'll take your house, if they need to set an example. They'll paint this town as lawless, and the very people you want to protect will lose everything when the contracts shutter."
    hide mika_tan
    show amaya_saito at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amaya_saito "I am already imagining them bulldozing the marsh before the ink dries on a court order that stops them. I am imagining the eelgrass ripped, the nests crushed —"

    lucas_herrera "I am imagining you in handcuffs,' he says, blunt as a tool. 'I don't want that image in my head."
    "His bluntness is a kind of tenderness. He doesn't say 'for my reputation' or 'for your safety' alone; he says it as if the two are braided: you and consequence."
    "A murmur rises as someone at the back stands — an older man with salt-bleached hair. He looks at you, then at the judge."

    "Older Man" "If we don't get the truth out, they'll call it safe and keep going. We can't just—"

    "Atlantech Counsel" "Objection, Your Honor. We are not in a political rally. This courtroom exists to adjudicate law, not to amplify loosed documents."

    "Judge" "Order! This court will determine admissibility through proper process. Ms. Saito, do you intend to submit anything now?"
    "The question lands like an ultimatum. Sweat prickles under your jacket despite the coolness of the room. Every face in the gallery is a tide mark: expectant, fearful, angry, trusting."
    "You think of the people who will be most harmed by any legal rebuke — fishers whose income is already thin, families renting rooms because their own houses are being appraised for buyouts. You think of"
    "the volunteers who have put their names down on lists and the kids who will inherit the marsh if it survives."
    "The court waits for you to shape the next move out of the clay of possibility."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A single, drawn breath seems to echo through the room]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low, oboe line — a descent]
    "You feel all your choices folding toward a single hinge. Whatever you choose now will not just be a legal strategy; it will rewrite the language the town uses about itself."

    jump chapter15
